title: Mining Points of Interest, North Korea Uncovered
name: Mining Points of Interest, North Korea Uncovered
description:
This is a kml file for mining points of interest from North Korea Uncovered. 

This Google Earth project offers an extensive mapping of North Korea's economic, cultural, political, and military infrastructures. Through the topic menu, users of this program have easy access to geographical information on North Korea's agriculture projects, aviation facilities, communications, hospitals, hotels, energy infrastructure, financial services, leisure destinations, manufacturing facilities, markets, mines, religious locations, restaurants, schools, and transportation infrastructure. In addition to locations of economic interest, this map also displays anti-aircraft locations, the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) and Northern Line Limit Line (NLL), incarceration facilities, political monuments, political residencies, military bases, and nuclear facilities.

properties.name: Anju Coal Field
properties.description: This is one of the largest coal fields in the DPRK, similar to the June 13 Coal Field in Undok County, North Hamgyong, or the Komdok Mine in South Hamgyong. Coal is extracted from the plains of Mundok County, a suburban area southwest of Anju, a large city in South Phyongan Province. The coal field has an estimated .9 billion tons of brown coal embedded both in the ground and under the ocean and bodies of water. Brown coal in the DPRK is widely used for its gases which are then used in factories.

properties.name: June 13 Coal Field
properties.description: This is 13 June Coal Field (formerly known as the Aoji Coal Mine). It is comprised of four large coal mines. There is an on-site chemical complex where the brown coal yielded from the mines is processed for industrial gases. This method mining brown coal and producing other energy sources from it is practiced in Canada and Australia, and was developed with technical cooperation from Russia.
